      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1–7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\nἘγένετο δὲ ἐν Ἰκονίῳ κατὰ τὸ αὐτὸ εἰσελθεῖν αὐτοὺς εἰς τὴν συναγωγὴν τῶν Ἰουδαίων καὶ λαλῆσαι οὕτως ὥστε πιστεῦσαι Ἰουδαίων τε καὶ Ἑλλήνων πολὺ πλῆθος.\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Ἐγένετο | Egeneto | G1096 | γίνομαι | V-ADI-3S | It came to pass / it happened |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | and / but / now |\n| 3 | ἐν | en | G1722 | ἐν | Prep | in / at |\n| 4 | Ἰκονίῳ | Ikoniō | G2430 | Ἰκόνιον | N-DSN | Iconium |\n| 5 | κατὰ | kata | G2596 | κατά | Prep | according to / in the same way |\n| 6 | τὸ | to | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASN | the |\n| 7 | αὐτὸ | auto | G846 | αὐτός | A-ASN | same |\n| 8 | εἰσελθεῖν | eiselthein | G1525 | εἰσέρχομαι | V-AAN | to enter |\n| 9 | αὐτοὺς | autous | G846 | αὐτός | P-APM | them (Paul and Barnabas) |\n| 10 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into |\n| 11 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 12 | συναγωγὴν | synagōgēn | G4864 | συναγωγή | N-ASF | synagogue |\n| 13 | τῶν | tōn | G3588 | ὁ | T-GPM | of the |\n| 14 | Ἰουδαίων | Ioudaiōn | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-GPM | Jews |\n| 15 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 16 | λαλῆσαι | lalēsai | G2980 | λαλέω | V-AAN | to speak |\n| 17 | οὕτως | houtōs | G3779 | οὕτως | Adv | in such a way / thus |\n| 18 | ὥστε | hōste | G5620 | ὥστε | Conj | so that / with the result that |\n| 19 | πιστεῦσαι | pisteusai | G4100 | πιστεύω | V-AAN | to believe / trust |\n| 20 | Ἰουδαίων | Ioudaiōn | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-GPM | of Jews |\n| 21 | τε | te | G5037 | τέ | Conj | and (both...) |\n| 22 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and (...and) |\n| 23 | Ἑλλήνων | Hellēnōn | G1672 | Ἕλλην | N-GPM | of Greeks |\n| 24 | πολὺ | poly | G4183 | πολύς | A-ASN | a great |\n| 25 | πλῆθος | plēthos | G4128 | πλῆθος | N-ASN | multitude / number |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nNow it happened in Iconium that they entered together into the synagogue of the Jews and spoke in such a way, so that a great multitude both of Jews and of Greeks believed.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nNow in Iconium, Paul and Barnabas went together into the Jewish synagogue and spoke in such a way that a great number of both Jews and Greeks believed.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nAnd so it came to pass in the city of Iconium, [continuing their established missionary pattern], they entered the Jewish synagogue together, [united in purpose and spirit]. They spoke [the gospel message] in such a manner—[with such Spirit-given power, clarity, and boldness]—that the direct result was a great multitude, composed of both Jews and [God-fearing] Greeks, came to believe.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:1–7 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong>\nἘγένετο δὲ ἐν Ἰκονίῳ κατὰ τὸ αὐτὸ εἰσελθεῖν αὐτοὺς εἰς τὴν συναγωγὴν τῶν Ἰουδαίων καὶ λαλῆσαι οὕτως ὥστε πιστεῦσαι Ἰουδαίων τε καὶ Ἑλλήνων πολὺ πλῆθος.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Ἐγένετο</td>\n<td>Egeneto</td>\n<td>G1096</td>\n<td>γίνομαι</td>\n<td>V-ADI-3S</td>\n<td>It came to pass / it happened</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / but / now</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>en</td>\n<td>G1722</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>in / at</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Ἰκονίῳ</td>\n<td>Ikoniō</td>\n<td>G2430</td>\n<td>Ἰκόνιον</td>\n<td>N-DSN</td>\n<td>Iconium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>κατὰ</td>\n<td>kata</td>\n<td>G2596</td>\n<td>κατά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>according to / in the same way</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>τὸ</td>\n<td>to</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASN</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>αὐτὸ</td>\n<td>auto</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>A-ASN</td>\n<td>same</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>εἰσελθεῖν</td>\n<td>eiselthein</td>\n<td>G1525</td>\n<td>εἰσέρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to enter</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>αὐτοὺς</td>\n<td>autous</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-APM</td>\n<td>them (Paul and Barnabas)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>συναγωγὴν</td>\n<td>synagōgēn</td>\n<td>G4864</td>\n<td>συναγωγή</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>synagogue</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GPM</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαίων</td>\n<td>Ioudaiōn</td>\n<td>G2453</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖος</td>\n<td>A-GPM</td>\n<td>Jews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>λαλῆσαι</td>\n<td>lalēsai</td>\n<td>G2980</td>\n<td>λαλέω</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to speak</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>οὕτως</td>\n<td>houtōs</td>\n<td>G3779</td>\n<td>οὕτως</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>in such a way / thus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>ὥστε</td>\n<td>hōste</td>\n<td>G5620</td>\n<td>ὥστε</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>so that / with the result that</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19</td>\n<td>πιστεῦσαι</td>\n<td>pisteusai</td>\n<td>G4100</td>\n<td>πιστεύω</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to believe / trust</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαίων</td>\n<td>Ioudaiōn</td>\n<td>G2453</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖος</td>\n<td>A-GPM</td>\n<td>of Jews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21</td>\n<td>τε</td>\n<td>te</td>\n<td>G5037</td>\n<td>τέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and (both...)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>22</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and (...and)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>23</td>\n<td>Ἑλλήνων</td>\n<td>Hellēnōn</td>\n<td>G1672</td>\n<td>Ἕλλην</td>\n<td>N-GPM</td>\n<td>of Greeks</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>24</td>\n<td>πολὺ</td>\n<td>poly</td>\n<td>G4183</td>\n<td>πολύς</td>\n<td>A-ASN</td>\n<td>a great</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>25</td>\n<td>πλῆθος</td>\n<td>plēthos</td>\n<td>G4128</td>\n<td>πλῆθος</td>\n<td>N-ASN</td>\n<td>multitude / number</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nNow it happened in Iconium that they entered together into the synagogue of the Jews and spoke in such a way, so that a great multitude both of Jews and of Greeks believed.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nNow in Iconium, Paul and Barnabas went together into the Jewish synagogue and spoke in such a way that a great number of both Jews and Greeks believed.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nAnd so it came to pass in the city of Iconium, [continuing their established missionary pattern], they entered the Jewish synagogue together, [united in purpose and spirit]. They spoke [the gospel message] in such a manner—[with such Spirit-given power, clarity, and boldness]—that the direct result was a great multitude, composed of both Jews and [God-fearing] Greeks, came to believe.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The faithful and Spirit-filled proclamation of the gospel is God's chosen method for creating faith and building His diverse Church.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The verse addresses the deep-seated ethnic and religious hostility that divides humanity (the individual and corporate FCF). It also addresses the tendency to rely on human methods and eloquence rather than the simple power of the gospel message delivered in the Spirit's power.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before we are called to speak, we are reminded that it is Christ who has already \"broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility\" (Eph 2:14). The unity we seek to foster through the gospel is a reality He has already accomplished on the cross. The power in our speech is not our own, but that of the Holy Spirit, who was sent because of Christ's finished work.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Seek opportunities to share the gospel message clearly and simply, trusting the Holy Spirit for the results.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart that is free from ethnic or social prejudice, seeing all people as potential brothers and sisters in Christ.\n    *   *Relational:* Intentionally build relationships and share fellowship within your local church with people from different backgrounds than your own, celebrating the unity Christ creates.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your sphere of influence, model and speak for a unity that is grounded not in political compromise but in the shared truth of the gospel.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):**\n    1.  **Attribute(s) of God surfaced:** God's sovereign power to save and His heart for the unity of all peoples in His Son.\n    2.  **One-sentence doxology:** Lord, we praise You that Your Word has the power to cut through all human division and create one new family in Jesus Christ.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> The faithful and Spirit-filled proclamation of the gospel is God's chosen method for creating faith and building His diverse Church.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The verse addresses the deep-seated ethnic and religious hostility that divides humanity (the individual and corporate FCF). It also addresses the tendency to rely on human methods and eloquence rather than the simple power of the gospel message delivered in the Spirit's power.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before we are called to speak, we are reminded that it is Christ who has already \"broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility\" (Eph 2:14). The unity we seek to foster through the gospel is a reality He has already accomplished on the cross. The power in our speech is not our own, but that of the Holy Spirit, who was sent because of Christ's finished work.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Seek opportunities to share the gospel message clearly and simply, trusting the Holy Spirit for the results.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a heart that is free from ethnic or social prejudice, seeing all people as potential brothers and sisters in Christ.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Intentionally build relationships and share fellowship within your local church with people from different backgrounds than your own, celebrating the unity Christ creates.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your sphere of influence, model and speak for a unity that is grounded not in political compromise but in the shared truth of the gospel.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong><ol>\n<li><strong>Attribute(s) of God surfaced:</strong> God's sovereign power to save and His heart for the unity of all peoples in His Son.</li>\n<li><strong>One-sentence doxology:</strong> Lord, we praise You that Your Word has the power to cut through all human division and create one new family in Jesus Christ.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:1 — \"...spoke in such a way that a great number...believed.\"\nKEY TERM:     οὕτως (houtōs, \"in such a way / thus\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Spirit-empowered speech creates a unified Church.\nIMAGE:        Light filling a synagogue, illuminating a mixed crowd of Jews and Greeks.\nAPPLICATION:  Share the simple gospel message this week, trusting the Spirit for the results.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the God whose Word unites all peoples in Christ.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:1 — &quot;...spoke in such a way that a great number...believed.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>οὕτως (houtōs, &quot;in such a way / thus&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Spirit-empowered speech creates a unified Church.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Light filling a synagogue, illuminating a mixed crowd of Jews and Greeks.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Share the simple gospel message this week, trusting the Spirit for the results.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the God whose Word unites all peoples in Christ.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt that what divides people—race, culture, background—is stronger than what could ever unite them? The book of Acts tells a different story. In the ancient city of Iconium, the apostles Paul and Barnabas walked into the local Jewish synagogue, the religious center of the city. They didn't have a flashy presentation or a marketing plan. They simply \"spoke in such a way,\" as Acts 14:1 puts it, that something incredible happened.\n\nThe power wasn't in their eloquence alone, but in the Holy Spirit working through their faithful proclamation of Jesus. The result was stunning: a huge crowd, made up of both devout Jews and seeking Gentiles (Greeks), believed the message. In a moment, the gospel created a new community where ethnic lines and old hostilities began to fade. This is a living picture of what Jesus accomplished on the cross, breaking down the dividing walls between us (Ephesians 2:14). It reminds us that the simple, bold message about Christ has a supernatural power to do what no human effort can: create one family out of a fractured world. Our job is to speak that message faithfully; the results belong to God.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt that what divides people—race, culture, background—is stronger than what could ever unite them? The book of Acts tells a different story. In the ancient city of Iconium, the apostles Paul and Barnabas walked into the local Jewish synagogue, the religious center of the city. They didn't have a flashy presentation or a marketing plan. They simply \"spoke in such a way,\" as Acts 14:1 puts it, that something incredible happened.</p>\n<p>The power wasn't in their eloquence alone, but in the Holy Spirit working through their faithful proclamation of Jesus. The result was stunning: a huge crowd, made up of both devout Jews and seeking Gentiles (Greeks), believed the message. In a moment, the gospel created a new community where ethnic lines and old hostilities began to fade. This is a living picture of what Jesus accomplished on the cross, breaking down the dividing walls between us (Ephesians 2:14). It reminds us that the simple, bold message about Christ has a supernatural power to do what no human effort can: create one family out of a fractured world. Our job is to speak that message faithfully; the results belong to God.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  Where did Paul and Barnabas go first upon arriving in Iconium?\n    A: They went to the Jewish synagogue.\n2.  What does the phrase \"spoke in such a way\" (οὕτως, *houtōs*) imply about their preaching?\n    A: It implies their preaching had a special quality, identified throughout Acts as boldness and power from the Holy Spirit, not just human skill.\n3.  What does this verse teach about the gospel's effect on people?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel has the divine power to bring people to faith and create a unified Church that transcends ethnic and cultural divisions like Jew and Greek.\n4.  Based on the apostles' example, what is one concrete action a believer can take?\n    A: I can share the simple gospel message with someone this week, trusting the Holy Spirit to give it power and produce the results.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Where did Paul and Barnabas go first upon arriving in Iconium?\n    A: They went to the Jewish synagogue.</li>\n<li>What does the phrase \"spoke in such a way\" (οὕτως, <em>houtōs</em>) imply about their preaching?\n    A: It implies their preaching had a special quality, identified throughout Acts as boldness and power from the Holy Spirit, not just human skill.</li>\n<li>What does this verse teach about the gospel's effect on people?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel has the divine power to bring people to faith and create a unified Church that transcends ethnic and cultural divisions like Jew and Greek.</li>\n<li>Based on the apostles' example, what is one concrete action a believer can take?\n    A: I can share the simple gospel message with someone this week, trusting the Holy Spirit to give it power and produce the results.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered witness expands to the ends of the earth.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: A resilient new start after persecution, showing the repeating mission pattern.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical narrative translated into a declarative anthem.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The Church Age, where Jew and Greek are made one in Christ.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The gathering of the great, diverse multitude that will worship the Lamb.\n\n***\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\nGate 1: PASS — Every line is justified by the verse's grammar, context, and canonical parallels.\nGate 2: PASS — The core verse is the Chorus; the verses unpack the implied context and content.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident in God's power; Bridge points to the final gathering.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery is drawn from the synagogue, speaking, and the mixed crowd.\nGate 5: PASS — The synthesis of strategy (Christian), synagogue context (Jewish), and ingathering (Midrashic echo) is present.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked across the song structure.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past event), V2 (present principle), Bridge (future hope); POV shifts in Bridge.\nGate 8: PASS — The Phi reveal is the Bridge's turn to \"we,\" the unified body.\nGate 9: PASS — Meter is consistently iambic; key words land on strong beats.\nGate 10: PASS — Consonantal texture shifts from the hard stops of \"dust\" and \"shook\" to the liquids of \"love\" and \"believe.\"\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the closed sounds of \"dust\" to the open sounds of \"grace\" and \"praise.\"\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 7-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law and the 2-second loop.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between sections.\nGate 14: PASS — The final word \"Lord\" is followed by a mental stop; the song is built for endurance.\nGate 15: PASS — The Chorus